Like if I thought of the word exterminate, it would make me think of eliminate eradicate annihilate, electrocute, things like that. guess_experiment: I think this experiment is trying to measure someone's overall creativity, their ability to recount a story in a fragmented sense, and their ability to switch between two seemingly irrelevant tasks possibly to see if words or themes from the story would bleed into their thoughts whenever they write their next set of words.
wcg_diff_general: Some words I thought of when they were pertinent to the story, like dirt, sand, water, things like that. But I purposely tried to keep my words irrelevant to the story to better show off my creativity instead of taking the easy way out and just thinking of words that would have something to do with the story.
volition_explanation: I was reflecting on the story when I read it, but I was purposely trying to think of words that had nothing to do with the story. I felt like it wasn't really that much of showcasing my creativity or other resourcefulness if I would've just thought of words because they came into my head from reading the story. Also, this was a very strange story. It almost seemed like the man discovered a dead body of a naked and perhaps decapitated girl and didn't really care because he was too interested in drinking or soliciting sex from his semi unwilling wife.
wcg_diff_explanation: The story almost got me a little bit irritated and mad because of how idiotic or careless or reckless the woman's husband was. For what I was reading in the story, it seemed like he and his friends discovered a dead body of a naked girl and didn't report it because they just wanted to enjoy their trip. But how overly pragmatic he was about it got me irritated. I was picturing a classic middle aged guy that doesn't really care about much and just drinks his problems away and solicit sex from his semi unwilling wife.  He doesn't really seem to care that much that he discovered the naked and I think decapitated body of a girl. I don't know if it made my ability to recount words better or worse, but it probably did change my thinking process.
clarity_explanation: I wasn't sure if I was allowed to mention pronouns or names, so when they were floating in my head they kind of impaired me because I had to stop and think of a different word at some point.
open_box: I mentioned this before, but this story was highly unusual and got me fairly irritated. I mean it really sounded like a guy that just wanted to go fishing or camping and drink with his buddies and pretty much ignored the fact that they found the body of a naked dead girl. It also was kind of implied to me that he was almost like indirectly pressuring or forcing his wife to have sex with him. Like he was drowning his problems away in whiskey or bouts of other alcohol and sex. I came to strongly dislike the husband, whatever his name was. I don't remember if he was Mel or if that was someone different. I feel bad for Claire. If that is what the wife's name was.  I wish I would've read some more about these Maddox Twins, they seemed like interesting characters and I don't think they were mentioned enough about the crimes they committed or anything about them.

guess_experiment: The effect of reading an emotional/interesting story on the words we think about/remember.
wcg_diff_general: I didn't need to come up with an arbitrary method to think up words. I just focused on different subjects that came up during the story.
volition_explanation: There were definitely things that were very vivid in my mind from the story and I focused on writing those things down. Each word was part of a grouping where the first word was an intentional choice based on something I remembered. The follow-ups in that grouping were for the most part also related to the story or things that were related to the first word, but I often found my mind connecting one grouping to the next via the last word of that grouping. It was interesting that once I got started the flow was very smooth from writing one word to another and connecting things via stream of thought and things that didn't seem important in the story but suddenly came up as a memory as I was writing.
wcg_diff_explanation: In the first word chain I struggled to come up with words and had to rely on a strategy to stay engaged for 3 minutes just writing random words. I actually use this tactic when I'm trying to fall asleep so it got REALLY tiresome. After the story I had a strong context and vivid imagery I could draw on to come up with words (I also didn't have to come up with that many words because I was just writing back things that came to mind from the story I'd just read).
open_box: That was a really interesting story, but I felt like breaking up the quoted sentences made it very difficult to read. I think as a Millennial who has actually read a lot of books growing up, I'm heavily dependent on punctuation and the shape of what I'm reading to help me sort out how to associate thoughts/talking with the thinker/speaker. Other than that, I found myself reading faster and faster as I got into the rhythm and I felt like none of my comprehension was lost. It definitely helped that the story was really engaging.
